hints_latex:
Put \emph{y\textsubscript{1}} and \emph{y\textsubscript{2}} in a vector
like this

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y} = \begin{bmatrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \end{bmatrix}
\end{align*} Now the given
equation is just a linear system with coefficient matrix \emph{A}.

statement_latex:
Consider the system of linear differential equations given by

\begin{align*}
y'_{1}(t) &= 3y_{1}(t) - 2y_{2}(t)\\
y'_{2}(t) &= 4y_{1}(t) - y_{2}(t)
\end{align*}

Express this system in the form of $y'(t) = Ay(t)$
